In Nginx there are two ways to turn on SSL for a server:

```
server {
  listen 443 ssl;
}
```

```
server {
  listen 443;
  ssl on;
}
```

Our Nginx plugin doesn't understand the latter. In parser.py's `get_vhosts`, the `VirtualHost` object will be created with `ssl = False`, leading later code to attempt to "enable" SSL on that vhost, creating a fatal conflict for the ssl_certificate directive. One possible easy fix: Look for `ssl_certificate` to determine whether a vhost has ssl enabled, instead of looking at the `listen` or `ssl` directives.

In my version of the package (pip reports version `5.0.2`, but [there might be some versioning issues at the moment](https://github.com/django-ckeditor/django-ckeditor/issues/211#issuecomment-165086488)), when I use the Image Browser (after pressing the "Browse Server" button), the large image preview and the "Embed Image" button are too far off to the right. I have to enlarge the Browser window that launches to see the entire image, as well as press the "Embed Image" button. 

I get the same behavior in Firefox, Chrome and Safari (haven't checked Opera or IE). I am able to fix the problem by removing `min-width:980px` on the `#container` element: 

```css
#container {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    /* min-width: 980px; */
    padding: 0;
}
```

There is no need for the `min-width` style in the css because you set an explicit inline style on [line #24 of `browse.html`](https://github.com/django-ckeditor/django-ckeditor/blob/master/ckeditor_uploader/templates/ckeditor/browse.html#L24): `<div id="container" style="width: 880px">`

So it seems that maybe these conflicting widths are causing the problem?


