Hi,

This is probably going to be another "hard to reproduce" bug, but I would like to file it for reference (and maybe to figure out a better way to communicate failures).

Using JavaSMT I was testing running solvers with multiple threads, and I get the bug shown in the issue title when running the following piece of code:

``` java
  private class SolverRunner extends Thread {
    @Override
    public void run() {
      try {
        // Creates a new Z3 context.
        SolverContext localContext = factory.generateContext(solverToUse());
        for (int i=0; i<5; i++) {
          try (ProverEnvironment pe = localContext.newProverEnvironment()) {
            Fuzzer f = new Fuzzer(localContext.getFormulaManager(), new Random(i));
            pe.push(f.fuzz(10000, 3));
            pe.isUnsat();
          }
        }
      } catch (InvalidConfigurationException|InterruptedException|SolverException pe3) {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Fail");
      }
    }
  }

  @Test
  public void testMultithreading() throws InterruptedException {
    List<Thread> threads = new ArrayList<>();
    int noThreads = 4;
    for (int i=0; i<noThreads; i++) {
      threads.add(new SolverRunner());
    }
    threads.forEach(Thread::start);
    for (Thread t : threads) {
      t.join();
   }
 }
```

Though the JavaSMT API is used, I think the intent is obvious: fuzzer generates a random formula, and then it's checked for satisfiability.
Due to interleavings, the failure is non-deterministic and happens about 1/2 of the time.

Hi,
I discover a little bug i cannot resolve with the actual Mixin, here the code :

        class KidSerializer(ExpanderSerializerMixin, serializers.ModelSerializer):
                guardian_kid = serializers.HyperlinkedRelatedField(view_name='guardian-kid-detail')

                class Meta:
                    model = GuardianKid
                    fields = (
                        'guardian_kids',
                    )
                    expandable_fields = {
                        'guardian_kids': (GuardianSerializer, (), {'many'=True}
                    }

        class GuardianKidSerializer(ExpanderSerializerMixin, serializers.ModelSerializer):
                kid = serializers.HyperlinkedRelatedField(view_name='kid-detail')

                class Meta:
                    model = GuardianKid
                    fields = (
                        'kid',
                    )
                    expandable_fields = {
                        'kid': KidSerializer
                    }

With that, you cannot use **GuardianSerializer** before you declare it (that's normal). So I tried to handle this like in [Django Model Foreign Key](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.8/ref/models/fields/#foreignkey) by using the name instead of the class

        class KidSerializer(ExpanderSerializerMixin, serializers.ModelSerializer):
                (...)
                expandable_fields = {
                    'guardian_kids': ('GuardianSerializer', (), {'many'=True}
                }

But it raise an error : _the first parameters has to be a class_. I also try to hook the __init__ in order to declare an self.Meta.expandable_fields

I think that can be handle easily like in Django, in file _expander/serializers.py_ at the line 41 instead of just look for a Class, you can try if it's a Class or a String.

    # Using sys.module <<< IMHO I'll go with this one
    import sys
    getattr(sys.modules[__name__], String)

    # Using eval !!!WARNING!!! is commonly admit eval() is a bad practice
    eval(String)

    # Using global()
